There's no such thing as a free lunch. 

What you want is out there for the taking.  It's not going to be handed to you. 

The value that you achieve from the outcome, will be in direct correlation to what you had to give to get it. 

As we are heading down the homestretch in 2022, lets be clear on what you want and then go get it. 
Everything you want, is there for you.  It  comes down to whether you're willing to do what it takes. 

The path to where you want to go will be long.  It will be hard.  It will be strenuous. 
Most importantly, it will be worth it. ✅

Amazing blast from the past, back to the mid-2000s when I had the privilege to visit Hawaii, work with the great Dean Sato and his players at Mililani High School, and do some work at Punahou HS. 

Thank you to the Champion Edge Foundation for having me over all those years back. Your investment into mental performance and your vision for what it takes to be a champion was truly groundbreaking. 

It's been almost two decades since this photo was taken... 

The logo has changed, the beard has grown, the passion has stayed the same… 

BLESSED EVERY DAY TO DO WHAT I GET TO DO.

#dominatetheday

Exciting morning celebrating @kenkoshio 1000th straight day hiking Piestewa Peak in Phoenix, AZ. 

Every morning since March 23, 2020, Ken has carried his drum up this hike to welcome the sun. 

His consistency is unmatched.

Piestewa Peak is named in honor of Army Spc. Lori Ann Piestewa - the first known Native American woman to die in combat in the U.S. Military and the first female soldier to be killed in action in the 2003 Iraq War.

Special thank you to all of our Armed Service team members and warriors. 

As we hike toward 2023, let’s embrace consistency and the mundane moments that come with it. 
Let us become machines of routine - that way, we can become the best version of ourselves and better serve others. 

Thank you, @drseandrake @athleteempowered, for getting me up here. 
#accountabilitypartners

The hike was powered by #jockoGO -  I should’ve brought a backpack full of @jockofuel to empower everyone at the top.

If you want more, you have to BECOME MORE. ⬇️

How do you become more? 
✅ By executing the proper training.
✅ Developing the right mindset (hire a coach).
✅ Learning from your coach's experience and expertise. 

If you were to have heart surgery, would you ever go to a doctor with no experience? 

NO WAY ‼️

You would find the doctor who has dedicated their life to heart surgery and has walked the walk with experience and a proven track record of success. 👍

Elite mental performance tips from @themayorsofficemlb. 

One of my favorite lessons I have heard in mental performance came from @themayorsofficemlb , when he spoke about his 3 Keys to Keep It Simple. 

Sean’s 3 keys when playing were:

- See the ball
- Be easy
- Hammer it 

In this video, you see a very similar approach when Sean is talking about Juan Soto’s struggles at the plate. 

Notice that Sean does mention Juan Soto getting back to his roots and driving the ball the other way… but with that, the emphasis gets back to his approach of keeping it simple and focusing on the things that are in his control. 

Here are the three tips @themayorsofficemlb has for a struggling hitter:

- Breathe (see it deep) 
- Use failure as feedback (attack and adjust) 
- Focus on the process 

These three mental performance nuggets apply to all areas of our lives.  In sports, life, relationships, work, whatever it is there will be adversity. 

When you face adversity make it your advantage. 

With that the strategies of breathing, using failure as feedback and being process oriented are simple, effective ways to get back to the present moment. 

When you’re in the present moment, thats where optimal performance happens. 

Thank you to @themayorsofficemlb for sharing this with the world.

In this video @georgesstpierre drops a couple Mental Performance bombs… 💣

🧠 💣 1️⃣ Support. Working with a Mental Performance Coach 
🧠 💣 2️⃣ Mental Imagery Training
🧠 💣 3️⃣ Present Moment Focus 

Let’s break each one down:

1️⃣ Support. Working with a Mental Performance Coach 

GSP speaks out about working with a Mental Performance Coach and the stigma that came along with it. This video is from 2007… GSP was ahead of his time.  His ability to recognize that EVERYONE needs a coach no matter the job/rank/endeavor.  It is no wonder that GSP is one of the greatest of all time. 🐐

2️⃣ Mental Imagery Training

Things ALWAYS happen twice - first in your mind.  Then in reality. 

We attacked mental imagery by putting GSP into situations that may occur in the fight, PRIOR to the fight. 

We practiced everything… something as small as how he walked out to the octagon to more intense moments like how he could come back to present moment focus when mental and physical adversity showed up. We even practiced his post fight process of transitioning from GSP the @UFC fighter to GSP the person. 

Everything was detailed.  Practicing this everyday ensured that come the night of his fight at #UFC74 - nothing felt surprising.  As he says in the interview, “it made me feel like it was not the first time I was doing it, so everything was more comfortable.” 

3️⃣ Present Moment Focus 

On the night of the fight, the physical preparation is done, so the mental game quickly becomes the most important part. 🧠

Since the fighter that wins the fight is not the best fighter, but rather the one who fights the best that night, it is important to have the systems and routines to get present during the fight. 

Optimal performance occurs when you’re in the present moment.  It is necessary to have the systems and routines to get present, so you can perform at your best when it means the most. 

Thankful for my time working with the 🐐, @georgesstpierre.

The best players take the best showers. 🚿

What does that mean? 

It means that when the practice/game/work day ends, the individual takes a shower literally or figuratively, “showering” off who they were “at work”. 

🥎 Softball Coach ➡️ Being a wife 👰‍♀️
⚾️ Baseball Player ➡️ Student 👨‍🎓
💼 CEO ➡️ Being a dad/mom 👨‍👩‍👦

As @mattcarp13 discusses in the call we did together, being able to transition from baseball ➡️ husband/father actually allowed for him to be a better husband, dad and a better baseball player. 

He was able to be all in with his family when he was away from the game.  Performance had no impact for how Carp showed up. 👨‍👩‍👦

It also has improved his performance on the field - as soon as he transitions from street clothes ➡️ baseball uniform, he is present and has more to give as a professional baseball athlete. ⚾️

It is great to be invested in your craft, but with that there is often a misunderstanding that you must “constantly be on”. 

In reality being able to detach and “turn it off” allows you to give more when you do “turn it on”. 👍

BE WHERE YOU NEED TO BE WHEN YOU NEED TO BE THERE. 

When you’re being a dad, be present and invested in what your kids are doing.  
When you’re working, be all in on work, present and focused on the task at hand. 

Take a page out of @mattcarp13 book and implement this into your own personal journey. 

Take good showers! 🚿

Dominate the day. 👊🏻

If you want to do more, you must become more.  📈

Find someone that is doing what you want to do, and begin to mirror their process. 
Success leaves clues.

Before you ever get the result, you must first embody the characteristics of someone who is doing that.  

As @drjoedispenza says, if you want to change your personal reality, you must first change your personality.  

If you want to be a @MLB pitcher, you must have the routines, habits, characteristics of a @MLB pitcher.

You have little control of what goes on around you - you have total control of how you choose to respond to it.

E+R=O

But heres the thing… what got you here, wont get you there. 

Its important to continuously reflect and refocus on truly whats important. 

Having the ability to consistently have perspective / adapt to what it takes to get to the next level is necessary.  These are mental skills that can be TRAINED. 

Have you ever had this struggle? 
How are you seperating who from do? 

Reflect on it. Be intentional.

Loved this video @jimschloss22 shared with me. 

A mental performance masterclass put on by @freddyj_6 of the World Series Champions @rangers 

Some of my favorite takeaways:

• Always being ready - there will be a time in EVERYONES career where you are not the #1.  You must show up to the field everyday as the SAME player, ready to perform.  Being a consistent player comes from consistently working YOUR process. 

• WE over ME mindset - Travis says here - “How am I going to help this team win today?” 

REMEMBER: It isn’t all about you.  Put your ego aside and constantly ask yourself, just like Travis did - “What can I do to help my team win THIS GAME.” Sometimes that means going 2-3 with 2 doubles, sometimes that means cheering on / supporting your teammates. 

• Trusting your process - doing the work in the dark… EVEN WHEN NO ONE SEES IT.  Even when you are getting ZERO reward for it on the field.  The best in ANY PURSUIT play the long game and SURRENDER to the process… 

(Subtle reminder… your process is all you have control over. 🤷‍♂️)

• Take advantage of your opportunities - when your name is called, being mentally and physically ready to EXECUTE. 

• Check your ego at the door.  NO BCD - Blaming, Complaining and getting Defensive.  Understand your role and execute your role to your best ability. 

When teams are made up of mental performance warriors who pour their energy into the controllables and show up DAILY with consistency and a WE over ME mindset… they win… A LOT. 

Hence why the @rangers are the 2023 World Series Champions. 

Congratulations to @freddyj_6 and the @rangers on a phenomenal season. 

SUCCESS LEAVES CLUES.  Take notes. ✍️
